--- In junit@yahoogroups.com, Brendan Humphreys &lt;brendan@t...&gt; wrote:
&gt; Hi Nathan,
&gt; 
&gt; You can use the &quot;failonerror&quot; and &quot;resultproperty&quot; attributes of 
the 
&gt; &lt;java&gt; task to stop the build if the junit.textui.TestRunner 
returns 
&gt; non-zero (indicating test failure or error).
&gt; 
&gt; Having said that, I would personally recommend using the &lt;junit&gt; 
task 
&gt; that is provided in the Ant optional tasks package, because it 
gives you 
&gt; much better control of how your tests are executed and nicer 
reporting.
&gt; 
&gt; Regards,
&gt; -Brendan
&gt; http://www.thecortex.net
&gt; 
&gt; 
